<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910826-0030</DOCNO><DOCID>910826-0030.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- J. Makowski Co.:   Loans of $240 Million Set   To Finance Energy Plant</HL><DATE>08/26/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><CO>   BGC GE MTC PC TGT</CO><MS>BASIC MATERIALS (BSC)CONGLOMERATES (CGL)INDUSTRIAL (IDU)UTILITIES (UTI)</MS><IN>CONGLOMERATES (CGL)CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)GAS UTILITIES (GAS)DIVERSIFIED INDUSTRIAL (IDD)</IN><NS>PETROLEUM MARKET (PET)</NS><RE>CONNECTICUT (CT)MASSACHUSETTS (MA)MISSOURI (MO)NORTH AMERICA (NME)OHIO (OH)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   J. Makowski Co., a Boston energy development company, saidit received $240 million in loans from Chase Manhattan Bankto finance the construction of a natural-gas firedcogeneration facility in Springfield, Mass.   The 240-megawatt facility will provide steam to MonsantoChemical Co., a unit of Monsanto Co., and the electricity itproduces will be sold to several utilities in the region.</LP><TEXT>   The project was developed during the past four years by ajoint venture including Makowski; Bay State Gas Co., a unitof Summit Bancorp.; Tenneco Gas, a unit of Tenneco Inc.;General Electric Co. and PGandamp;E-Bechtel Generating Co., a jointventure involving Pacific Gas andamp; Electric Co. and BechtelGroup Inc. Construction is expected to take two years.   ---   Corrections andamp; Amplifications                                                                                                          BAY STATE GAS Co. isn't a unit of Summit Bancorp. asreported in yesterday's edition.   (WSJ August 27, 1991)</TEXT></DOC>